Summary:¶

There are 735 data points in each column, and the mean value of the "co2" column is 354.21 ppm with a standard deviation of 27.92 ppm. The mean value of the "temp" column is 57.60 degrees Celsius with a standard deviation of 0.40 degrees Celsius.

The minimum value of the "co2" column is 313.20 ppm, and the maximum value is 414.83 ppm. The minimum value of the "temp" column is 56.73 degrees Celsius, and the maximum value is 58.84 degrees Celsius. The median (50th percentile) value of the "co2" column is 351.34 ppm, and the median value of the "temp" column is 57.59 degrees Celsius. The 25th percentile of the "co2" column is 328.79 ppm, and the 75th percentile is 376.52 ppm. The 25th percentile of the "temp" column is 57.28 degrees Celsius, and the 75th percentile is 57.92 degrees Celsius.

From the plots, we can see a clear upward trend and seanal pattern for both datasets, and there are more noises in the temprature data.

def adf_kpss_test(data):
    # ADF test
    result_adf = adfuller(data)
    print('ADF Test:')
    print(f'ADF Statistic: {round(result_adf[0],3)}')
    print(f'p-value: {round(result_adf[1],3)}')
    print(f'Critical Values: {result_adf[4]}')
    #print whether the data is stationary or not at 1% significance level
    if abs(result_adf[0]) > abs(result_adf[4]['1%']) and result_adf[1] < 0.05:
        print('We can reject the null hypothesis at 1% significance level that the data is NOT stationary. The data is likely stationary')
    else:
        print('We cannot reject the null hypothesis at 1% significance level that the data is NOT stationary. The data is likely NOT stationary')
        
    # KPSS test
    result_kpss = kpss(data, nlags='auto')
    print('\nKPSS Test:')
    print(f'KPSS Statistic: {round(result_kpss[0],3)}')
    print(f'p-value: {round(result_kpss[1],3)}')
    print(f'Critical Values: {result_kpss[3]}')
    #print whether the data is stationary or not at 1% significance level
    if abs(result_kpss[0]) > abs(result_kpss[3]['1%']) and result_kpss[1] < 0.05:
        print('We can reject the null hypothesis at 1% significance level that the data is stationary. The data is likely NOT stationary')
    else:
        print('We cannot reject the null hypothesis at 1% significance level that the data is stationary. The data is likely stationary')
        
    if result_adf[0] > result_adf[4]['1%'] and result_kpss[0] > result_kpss[3]['1%']:
        print('The ADF and KPSS tests are giving conflicting results.')

b. Adjust seasonality, changepoint priors or other methods to see if you can create a better fit model. Examine the residuals. Using the predicted values and y train, calculate the following: MAE, MSE, MAPE, sMAPE, MASE. Can use prebuilt functions or calculate by hand.¶

In [ ]:
cutoffs = pd.to_datetime(['1975-02-15', '1985-02-15', '1995-02-15'])
In [ ]:
param_grid = {
    'seasonality_mode': ['additive' , 'multiplicative'],
    'changepoint_prior_scale': [0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 0.5],
    'seasonality_prior_scale': [0.01, 0.1, 1.0, 10.0],
    'holidays_prior_scale': [0.01, 0.1, 1.0, 10.0],
}

# Generate all combinations of parameters
all_params = [dict(zip(param_grid.keys(), v)) for v in itertools.product(*param_grid.values())]
rmses = []  # Store the RMSEs for each params here

# Use cross validation to evaluate all parameters
for params in all_params:
    m = Prophet(**params).fit(train)  # Fit model with given params
    df_cv = cross_validation(m, cutoffs=cutoffs, horizon='30 days', parallel="processes")
    df_p = performance_metrics(df_cv, rolling_window=1)
    rmses.append(df_p['rmse'].values[0])

tuning_results = pd.DataFrame(all_params)

Comment:¶

Adding additional regressor didn't improve model performance.

d. Give a summary of your modeling in prophet. What improved the model, what made the fit worse. Give your reasonings why this would happen given the patterns in the data.¶

I found that changing the seasonality_mode to 'multiplicative' improved the model, as it was able to better capture the non-linear relationship between the seasonal components and the trend. This was especially useful as the amplitude of the seasonal effect varied with the level of the trend. Additionally, including seasonality as a component in the model helped with the model performance.

On the other hand, larger changepoint_prior_scale values can result in a model that is too rigid and unable to capture important changes in the trend. The optimal value for changepoint_prior_scale will depend on the specific dataset and should be chosen through cross-validation.

Regarding the addition of an additional regressor 'co2', it is possible that this variable was not significantly correlated with the target variable 'temp', resulting in a negative impact on the model performance. However, it is also possible that the inclusion of the 'co2' variable introduced multicollinearity or overfitting to the model, leading to a decrease in performance. Therefore, it is important to carefully choose the regressors to include in the model based on domain knowledge and statistical significance tests.

Part 4. 10 pts – conclusion¶

a. Which was the best model according to your error metrics?¶

So far, ARIMA(2,2,1) model works the best according to the error metrics. There could be several reasons why the ARIMA(2,2,1) model outperformed Prophet in this case:

Data characteristics: ARIMA models work well when the data follows a stationary process, meaning that the statistical properties of the data remain constant over time. If the data has a clear trend and/or seasonality, then Prophet's ability to capture these patterns may be limited.

Model assumptions: ARIMA models have fewer assumptions compared to Prophet. For example, Prophet assumes that the seasonal pattern is fixed and does not change over time, whereas ARIMA models can handle time-varying patterns.

Model tuning: It's possible that the ARIMA model was better tuned for this particular dataset compared to the Prophet model. ARIMA models have several hyperparameters that can be tuned to optimize the model performance, including the order of differencing, AR and MA terms, and the inclusion of exogenous variables.

Sample size: The sample size of the dataset may also be a factor. ARIMA models tend to work better for smaller sample sizes, whereas Prophet may be more suitable for larger datasets.

d. If you had this data for 100 locations (different pairs of time series), how would you approach modeling this data?¶

If I had this data for 100 locations, I would approach modeling the data in a similar way as for a single pair of time series, but with some additional considerations:

Data exploration: I would explore each pair of time series separately to identify patterns and potential outliers.

Data processing: I would preprocess the data for each pair of time series separately, including missing value imputation, normalization, and detrending.

Model selection: I would test multiple models, including ARIMA, SARIMA, and Prophet, for each pair of time series and compare their performance using statistical metrics and visual inspection.

Model combination: Once I have identified the best models for each pair of time series, I would combine them using an appropriate approach, such as a hierarchical model, to account for the dependencies between the time series.

Cross-validation: I would use cross-validation to evaluate the performance of the models and ensure that they generalize well to new data.

Forecasting: Finally, I would use the selected models to make forecasts for each pair of time series and evaluate the results using appropriate metrics.
